\par
                  Point-defect avalanches mediate grain boundary\par
                  diffusion\par
                  Ian Chesser         1\u9993?   & Yuri Mishin         1\u9993?\par
\par
\par
\par
\par
                  Grain boundary diffusion in polycrystalline materials is a physical phenomenon of great\par
                  fundamental interest and practical signi\u64257?cance. Although accelerated atomic transport along\par
                  grain boundaries has been known for decades, atomic-level understanding of diffusion\par
                  mechanisms remains poor. Previous atomistic simulations focused on low temperatures\par
                  where the grain boundary structure is ordered or high temperatures where it is highly dis-\par
1234567890():,;\par
\par
\par
\par
\par
                  ordered. Here, we conduct molecular dynamics simulations of grain boundary diffusion at\par
                  intermediate temperatures most relevant to applications. A surprising result of this work is\par
                  the observation of intermittent GB diffusion behavior and its strong system-size dependence\par
                  unseen in previous work. Both effects are found to originate from thermally activated point-\par
                  defect avalanches. We identify the length and time scales of the avalanches and link their\par
                  formation to dynamic heterogeneity in partially disordered systems. Our \u64257?ndings have\par
                  implications for future computer modeling of grain boundary diffusion and mass transport in\par
                  nano-scale materials.\par
