                                                                                  defects and activates thousands of mobile atoms.\par
                                                                                     The questions then arise: how does an avalanche begin, and\par
                                                                                  how does it end? Careful structural analysis (see Methods) reveals\par
                                                                                  that a typical avalanche starts with the formation of an interstitial\par
                                                                                  atom in the GB core that hops multiple times (on the ps\par
                                                                                  timescale) before pushing a regular atom out of its preferred site\par
                                                                                  (Fig. 3b). This event triggers a cascade of collective structural\par
                                                                                  excitations with a string-like character in which multiple atoms\par
                                                                                  move simultaneously in the same direction. A string-like\par
                                                                                  excitation can be viewed as an extended Frenkel pair in which\par
                                                                                  the leading atom has an interstitial character (associated with\par
                                                                                  local compression) and the trailing atom has a vacancy character\par
                                                                                  (associated with local tension). This interpretation is con\u64257?rmed\par
                                                                                  by analyzing the free volume distribution in the population of\par
                                                                                  mobile atoms (see Supplementary Fig. 1). Importantly, the\par
                                                                                  avalanches involve the facilitated dynamics23,24 of the multiple\par
                                                                                  Frenkel pairs and neighboring string-like excitations. Namely, a\par
                                                                                  collective atomic displacement at one location triggers nearby\par
                                                                                  diffusive events, creating a positive feedback for further propaga-\par
                                                                                  tion of the atomic displacement \u64257?eld that rapidly grows in size\par
                                                                                  into a full-\u64258?edged avalanche. As the point-defect population\par
